animal.description: Meet Zorro! He is a 9 year old Beagle/Dachshund mix and weighs 17lbs. He is not as swashbuckling as Antonio Banderas, but definitely is just as handsome! Before coming to POA, Zorro was in a home with 7 other dogs. He and Mia, his "honey," had 6 puppies and they all lived together as one big happy family. Unfortunately, one of their owners passed away and POA stepped in to help. Right now, Zorro shares a pen with his daughter, Porsha. They are not a bonded pair, but the two love each other's company. If a family wishes to adopt both sweeties, we would certainly consider that option. Zorro is a super sweet guy who enjoys walks and loves to be petted and brushed. His diet needs to be managed with prescription food, but he is otherwise in good health. Zorro is good with other dogs (not sure about cats). Children over 10 years old may be okay. If you would like to know more about Zorro, please contact Stacey at stacey.doan@poainc.org or better yet, please complete an online application found at www.poainc.org.

Seeley is a female pup approximately 3 months old and appears to be a heeler mix.  She might have shepherd in her too but is likely a mix of several breeds or more. Without knowing the background information on them and exactly what breed(s) their parents are, its just an educated guess on our parts.

Our puppy adoption fee is $150.00 each and our pups have been spayed/neutered, wormed, vaccinated for kennel cough and have received their first parvo/distemper shot. We require a fenced yard or if you live in the country safe acreage on your own land for exercise. Our dogs must be allowed in their family home and be allowed to sleep inside of the home at night. At adoption you will be required to complete and sign an adoption contract. 

We are located in Billings, Montana and adopters to travel to our location.

If you would like to inquire about adopting this pup or have questions, please contact foster mom Sheri Lee at 406-208-3853.

animal.description: Meet Porsha! She is a 7 year old Pekingese/Dachshund mix and weighs 18lbs. Before coming to POA, Porsha was in a home with 7 other dogs. Zorro and Mia, his "honey," had 6 puppies and they all lived together as one big happy family. Unfortunately, one of their owners passed away and POA stepped in to help. Posha is Zorro and Mia's daughter and she has inherited their good looks and sweet personalities! She is a love bug who enjoys lots of pets, going for walks, and being lavished with affection. Right now, Porsha shares a pen with her dad, Zorro. They are not a bonded pair, but the two love each other's company. If a family wishes to adopt both sweeties, we would certainly consider that option. Porsha has advanced glaucoma in her right eye and after consulting with our veterinarian, the decision was made to remove her eye as the glaucoma will certainly worsen as she ages. Porsha is good with other dogs (not sure about cats). Children over 10 years old may be okay. If you would like to know more about Porsha, please contact Stacey at stacey.doan@poainc.org or better yet, please complete an online application found at www.poainc.org.

animal.description:
Oscar is a fun loving pup born on June 1, 2020. He did not do well with apartment living, and was surrendered to our rescue to find a more appropriate home.  He loves to play with his toys, other dogs, and has lived with young children. Oscar is curious about cats, but does not chase them and behaves appropriately when swatted or hissed at.  He is crate trained, housebroken, and rides well in vehicles.  We require obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs less than a year old, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6  years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Oscar will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Oscar will come with a neuter agreement to be neutered between the age of 18 - 24 months. Neutering large breed dogs has been linked to joint issues, and osteosarcoma. $100 of the adoption fee will be refunded once proof of neutering is provided. 

Adoption fee is $500

*****Belgian Malinois Adoption requirements*****

The dog you have selected is a Belgian Malinois.  This is a breed that has very specific needs for an adoptive home.  Because of their need for a high level of exercise, both mentally and physically and their need for ongoing training, only applicants with demonstrated owner/handler experience with this breed will be considered.  The vast majority of them are not best suited as family pets, but in homes with experienced handlers knowledgeable of their needs and breed characteristics.  We will not place in homes with small children or small dogs/cats.  

Clarabella


If you can give Clarabella an indoor forever home, please fill out our online application on our website at http://www.savingpawsrescueaz.com/adoption-form/  

 We will only schedule meet and greets with an approved application. We are an all-volunteer organziation.  It may take a couple of days to process an application and complete reference checks.

Thank you for your interest in saving a life!

animal.description:
Meet Walter the dog! 
 
While I can't wait to get to know you, here is a little about me. I was dropped off at the pound for being too big... and not just the thick kind of big. I am a 5-year-old yellow lab mix and I have the soul of an old man Walter. I do come with some challenges I hope you are willing to embrace. My name may be Walter but I cannot hear you due to being deaf but that does not stop me from loving you the most and giving you all the kisses and cuddles. I currently do not live with any other animals but I do not mind any other dogs or cats, I just do my own thing. I am potty and crate trained. While with my foster mom we have worked on my leash skills so when you meet me I will be a pro! When I get excited I do use my mighty muscles to try and get a good sniff everywhere so you might have to hold on tight for me. I will admit it, I kind of am a couch potato and not just because I look like a yummy bag of lays chips! I don't play with toys much but if you give me a good bone I will be happy for hours. Outside time is my favorite. My new favorite activity is getting to go for a car ride and flap my cheeks in the wind. So, if you are looking for the sweetest boy with the best attitude then I'm your number one guy! See you soon and I can't wait to meet you! Submit your applications online at: https://oneloveanimalrescue.com/pre-adoption-application/

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Wolfie (SC) is a male Boxer mix rescued in South Carolina and estimated to be 7 years old at intake in December 2020. This gorgeous boy's once happy world was turned upside when his owner passed away at home, leaving Wolfie trapped in the house with his owner's body. Wolfie is safe now, has received some TLC with our vet partner for a skin condition and is looking for a forever home where he can live his best life and be happy again.
Wolfie is very gentle with people, very polite with other dogs and not bothered by cats. He will do best with older children. He

rarely barks, is house trained and rarely pulls on the leash unless he sees a squirrel in close range. He is lower energy, mostly a couch potato, loves to snuggle and is a bit of a Velcro dog - he attaches quickly to his humans and follows them from room to room. He is very food motivated and

loves soft treats, as well as Kongs with peanut butter and puzzle toys. Looking into Wolfie's soulful eyes, you can see he appreciates the love he feels from you.
If you can right Wolfie's world and be his return to happiness, please apply online to adopt Wolfie (SC) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description:
Meet adorable 57 pound and two-year-old read the squatty bully. This adorable boys sadly was left behind and found by housekeeping in a hotel. He had a crappy owner who decided it wasn’t worth picking him up. He is a friendly and happy little guy. When he first came to the shelter he was extremely shut down and hiding in the corner. But he quickly made friends. He would make a great companion or be a happy second dog. He loves to go for walks and car rides. He’s also Food motivated and would benefit from basic training

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $300, which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

Hopper is a super sweet playful dog who loves everyone. He is very self entertaining. He is house broke. This is the happiest dog you will ever meet. He is great with dogs.

We are looking for someone who would be dedicated to keep his legs as limber as they can be for as long as they can be and can deal with a disabled dog down the road. 

Also, he would do best in a home that has no small children or children really at all.

animal.description:
Meet Danny Boy!

8-year-old Danny Boy and

13-year-old Hugo

are a bonded pair of adorable chihuahuas! Sadly, they were relinquished to the San Diego Humane Society-Oceanside by their owner who could no longer care for them due to financial hardships. They became Frosted Faces on January 24th.

The shelter staff described Hugo (the black & white one) as a super-stellar, super-sweet senior with a big heart. His buddy, Danny Boy (the brown one) was described as nervous meeting new people, but he seems to have gotten over that! Step into our littles rooms and he's one of the first to come up to say hi! Hugo prefers to find a comfy bed to nap in, but he doesn't mind being picked up and snoozing in your arms instead!

The shelter performed dental surgery on Hugo on January 15th. He has dry eye and receives eye drops twice a day, and recovering from skin and ear infections. Danny Boy also has ear infections, a heart murmur, skin issues, and a soft mass under the skin on the left lower chest. Danny Boy will be visiting our vet for diagnostics.

Both boys left on a 2-week Frosted Fling yesterday, and they get to share their Fling home with FF Poet (who is also available for adoption)! We look forward to learning how these two cuties are in a home environment. Check back soon for an update!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/27/21 KG

animal.description:
Meet Nash!

Nash is currently in a foster home, but available for meet and greets with appointment. Nash is shy with new people, but once he knows you he is quite snuggly. He also enjoys playing with and snuggling with other dogs. (We feel like Nash would thrive in a home with another dog). He knows sit, shake, down, drop and come. Nash would do better in a home with no small children as he is startled with loud noises and very timid. Additionally, he loves to play with bones and toys and can get wound up easily and mouthy. Nash loves being a couch potato and will gladly sleep in your bed (if allowed). He is house trained.
Nash really needs a home with people who don't work all day, he does NOT do well in a crate. 
Nash would do best in a home with people who don't work all day. In his foster home, he did fine being left alone for short periods loose. Being crated gives Nash a lot of anxiety, so he needs a home he won't need to be crated. Perhaps a home with a nice fenced yard, or a doggy door or a family who works from home. 
If you feel like Nash would be a good fit for you and your family, please contact us for an appointment.

animal.description:
Meet Lotus! Lotus is a beautiful, 2 year old girl looking for her furever home! Lotus was found as a lost girl and was brought into the shelter on 1/19. Lotus is very frightened of the shelter and the new, unknown environment. With a little compassion from the volunteers, Lotus has shown her sweet side. She is treat motivated, so her trust can be won over with a few good treats. Lotus knows how to sit on command, and she is eager to learn more tricks for more delicious snacks! Lotus has a beautiful smile, and with a little TLC, bonding, and time to adjust, she will be her bright, beautiful, loving self for her new family! Get to know and fall in love with this 54 pound sweetheart in run 78. Her ID number is 626952. Lotus is up-to-date on vaccines, and she will be spayed, microchipped, and heart worm tested upon adoption. She can't wait to start loving her new family!

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description:
Pepper is a handsome 7-year-old male Shih Tzu that weighs 25 pounds. He is very overweight, and needs to lose at least 5-8 pounds. He is the sweetest little guy that will make the perfect companion for anyone! He is mostly blind in 1 eye from advanced cataracts, but it doesn't slow him down one bit! He loves exploring the backyard, enjoys the company of other dogs, is fantastic with small kids, and is very social. He is an easy going and low maintenance dog. He is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative, recently had a dental, and microchipped. He is $350 plus TX sales tax with an approved application: www.recycledpomsbcs.com/adopt

Texas law requires that all humane organizations (Rescues, SPCA's, Humane Societies, State nonprofit, and charitable 501c3 exempt orgs) collect and remit sales and use tax to the Texas Comptroller on their adoption fees.

We do not ship or transport our dogs. We require all adopters to meet the dog in person to ensure it is a good fit. We represent the dog to the best of our ability and since they are in rescue, we do not always get their history.

Please note: We are a non-profit Pomeranian Rescue with dogs in private foster homes. We do not have a facility open to the public. We require an approved application before a potential adopter is introduced to a dog. We contact vet references to ensure animals in the home are current on vaccinations, heart worm prevention, and sterilization. We do not adopt our dogs to homes in which an animal is not spayed or neutered. A home visit may be required.

Please visit our website for more information and an adoption application. www.recycledpomsbcs.com

animal.description: 2-year-old Hermes will amaze you with his plethora of creative abilities and innate talents. Hermes displayed his non-stop energy as he leapt skyward, chased down, cornered, and retrieved every genre of squeaky toy in the Humane Society arsenal.  His intensely bright, blue eyes are always focused on you, asking for just one more toss, one more game and one more challenge. The human obliged by dropping a hotdog treat into the hollow pink ball. Hermes first tried the obvious but couldn’t get his head far enough in to reach the treat. Then, after a moment’s thought, he tilted his head and approached the toy, extended his paw, and gave it a bump sufficient to roll it over so the treat simply fell out. He received his name for adroitly mimicking one of most clever and mischievous of all the ancient Greek hero’s. Hermes also has a passionate devotion to his human family and would be happiest in a home that doesn’t entertain a lot of guests. When asked what he would like to tell the humans who might be interested in his adoption, Hermes replied, “Check out my tail….it is a perfect example of a spiral that conforms to the Fibonacci numeric sequence found everywhere in nature.” Quite a creative canine.

animal.description: Hank is a 1 yr old Beagle mix that is 25lbs! He likes to play with the resident dog for a bit, then loses interest. He would be fine with or without another dog in the home. He has been around cats and is non-reactive. He is a little skittish, so calmer kids would be best. He knows to sit and is very treat motivated, great on a leash and harness during walks but loves to jump when he wants attention. He will go in the crate but he is not a huge fan. He prefers the wire pen over the crate. He is doing well with potty training and the foster family is using a bell. He seems to prefer cuddle time over playtime but will run around outside! He does hate to be picked up and loud noises or sudden movements tend to scare him. He has some minor separation anxiety and will follow the foster family around the house. His adoption fee is $460.

animal.description:
Frost is a sweet and mellow 9-year-old Chihuahua! He does have cataracts in both eyes and is blind, he is also deaf, but it doesn't stop him one bit! He came to TNT after he and 4 other chihuahuas were found in their deceased owners' home. They all had very bad flea dermatitis, ear infections, and just poorly cared for. After coming to us, he has had all medical needs taken care of. Frost has had 11 infected teeth removed, been neutered, received antibiotics for his skin, and is starting to feel and look much healthier!
His schedule consists of: Eat, sleep, snuggle, repeat. He's happiest with his human, especially males. He will need slower paced home with a family that will shower him with cuddles and belly rubs. He doesn't wander off but does get lost easily, and with being blind & deaf, a fenced-in yard is required. Having another senior dog in his future home to keep him company when the humans aren't isn't a must, but we are sure he would love it!

He's just as sweet as can be, even with all his issues. His tail wags as soon as he realized you are near, and can't wait to snuggle. He is a major cuddle bug that deserves a home that will give him all the cuddles he wants! Frost's adoption fee is $300.

animal.description:
**Available for Adoption**
Please be within 60-90 minutes of Delmar NY

Nova, guesstimated age 4-6,  is a big beautiful girl, weighing in at 74lbs.  She’s at a good weight finally, and stands very tall.  She has huge amazing ears, and is a very sweet girl. 
Over 3 months ago, she was found in awful shape, very thin, and giving birth to puppies on a lawn.  Only one puppy survived. 
She had Heartworm (which she’s been fully treated for) and X-rays revealed hip dysplasia and some arthritis in the spine. The vet feels strongly that it’s from rough breeding. 
She is not in any pain from either, and all she needs right now is her daily bone and joint supplement. 

She’s friendly to all people. 
She’s a bit anxious about seeing other dogs she doesn’t know, but we think this is mostly over her only surviving puppy. 
As of today, her puppy has a new home.  (No guarantees—>) but suspect this will subside quite a bit without her puppy around. 
It’s best for Nova to go to a home without other dogs. 
(Cats unknown) 

She does very well with good leadership and her new found leash/walking skills. Otherwise, she can be very strong on the leash.  

She rides well in the car. Crate trained, although she’d rather hang out with her person. 

All around Nova is just sweet, a big love, and of course beautiful. She will make someone very happy. 

She has been a wonderful mom to her pup, and now it’s her time to finally get a loving forever home of her own. 

If you think Nova might be the right match for you, please consider submitting an application, so we can learn more about you.    

If you are interested in adopting from GSRNY, please look into our adoption process on our website, and please read below, before contacting us, and please visit our website:

- PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE POST & visit our website BEFORE INQUIRING ABOUT ADOPTION -

All of our dogs are fully vetted before adoption.
Copies of all medical records will go to adopters. 
**Vet appointment dates must be scheduled by adopters and date given to GSRNY before an adoption can take place. 

**Due to the Pandemic Restrictions:
Please be able to print, scan and send all paperwork between you and GSRNY through email in PDF format. 
Have the ability to video your home, inside and out. 
We are thankful for satellite, so we can see your location. 

**Excellent vet history and references are a must. 

**We ask that adopters have plenty of time to work with an adopted dog/puppy. 
Please do keep in mind, your regular work schedule.  The Pandemic has changed schedules for some, but should always be training and preparing for regular work hours & schedules** 

**Our adoption Process may not be for everyone, or the distance too far. Please check out your local shelters and rescues. There are so many animals in need everywhere, we are only one of many.

**If you are considering adopting from GSRNY, please first read through our adoption process, details and fees. If you are still interested in moving forward, you’ll also find our adoption application to download and print out, and send back to us PDF format. 
www.GSRNY.org

NAME: Tyson
Age: 6 yrs old
Breed: Great Dane
Sex: male
Weight: 135 lbs
Location: Coldwater, ON
Spayed/Neutered: Yes, I am neutered.  
Kids/Cats/Dogs: Not suited for young children. I chase cats. I am not keen on male dogs, a calm quiet female would be OK. I would be OK as the only dog. 
Car rides: I'm great in the car.
Crate/house trained: I may bark at noises, but I am good in the house. I am crate trained but dont need to be. 
Leash walks: I am strong, and I can be reactive when seeing other dogs on a walk. Ideally a quiet setting, and a strong knowledgeable leader would be best. 
Vacc/worming/flea: UTD on vaccinations? Flea/tick, worming? Vet checked? Microchipped? 

Hi, my name is Tyson! I was surrendered to FEF so I could find a better suited home. I wasnt getting along with the other dog in the house. My owner was ill, and it became too much to manage. I needed to find a place that I can live happily. I am a typical big goofy dane. I like to carry my stuffy around. I like to cuddle, and sleep on the couch. I wouldnt mind sharing your bed too. I am a good boy, and I do bark at anything I'm unsure of, maybe a noise or a knock at the door. I have a food allergy, and I thrive best on a raw diet. I love people, and warm up very fast to strangers. I dont like small children. Older children are fine. I love playing with my toys. I would be just fine as the only dog in the home. If you are OK with a little slobber, and a gentle giant taking over your furniture ? maybe I can be your new best friend. Fill out an application here:

Email my foster mom for more information fureverfriendsadoption@gmail.com

animal.description:
Name: Midori (Dori)

Sex: Female

Color: Black/white

Eye Color: Blue

Birthday: 10/16/19

Weight: 50 lbs

Large Dog Friendly: Yes

Small Dog Friendly: Unknown

Cat Friendly: In her previous home she played with 2 dog-savvy cats.

Crate Trained: In process, we are working on it.

Housebroken: Yes

Energy Level: High

Reaction to New People: Friendly, jumpy, licks, and will mouth if you try to play with her.

Kid Friendly: Very Kid Friendly

Training: Knows sit, lay down, drop, and kennel. Sometimes she chooses when she will listen.

Grooming Needs: Midori has a standard husky coat which will require frequent brushing. 

Fence: She would do fine with a fenced yard or a tie-out. She does not seem interested in jumping the fence, but she has resident dogs to play with her.

Solo or Siblings: She would do well as an only dog or with siblings that are willing to stand up to her.

From the foster: Hello, my name is Midori but I go by Dori. I am a very energetic but loveable one-year-old. I have some basic training skills, I can sit, lay, and drop but like any husky, sometimes I don't like to listen. I am okay at walking but I like to stop and sniff constantly. I really only pull when I am on walks with my foster furr-sister. When I see people I like to stop and hope that they will come pet me. 

I am great with kids, I have a one-year-old human foster sister and we get along great. I let her pet me and sometimes she gives me hugs or lays her head on me, I like that. Sometimes I knock her over but only on accident. I like to give her kisses. I do like her stuffed animals and if you leave me alone with them they might get "defluffed."

I like to play fetch with balls and my toys. I like to play and chase my husky foster sister. Sometimes I can play too rough and can play too much. I would benefit from a dog that could show my boundaries and tell me no. 

My foster home has a fenced-in yard and I like to hang out there and run. I haven't tried to escape but I do have a prey drive so I can't promise I won't try to escape. 

I am not a fan of my kennel but I am learning. I usually need some resurgence that my family is still with me when they go to bed so usually they come out of the room and let me know it's bedtime and I settle in for the night. They usually sleep until 7:30 and I don't ever wake them up. My foster family is usually always home so I have not spent much time in the kennel during the day. I would love to be left outside my kennel but you may come home to a mess if you leave toys or blankets out. 

Overall my foster family loves me and says I am a great dog. I have not had any big issues and despite my energy level I would make an amazing friend!

Adoption Fee: $400

All dogs coming into Adopt a Husky Minnesota receive care tailored to their needs, including: Nose-to-tail exam with a partner veterinarian, Vaccinations (Rabies, Distemper, Bordetella), 4DX test to check for heartworm or tick exposure, Fecal Analysis, Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative, Spay/Neuter prior to adoption, Microchip, and are evaluated for temperament and trainability.

animal.description:
Blache is a 6.5-year-old. Chihuahua who came to TNT after her along with 4 other senior Chihuahua's, were found alone, starving, and in a terrible condition after it was discovered that their owner was deceased. We are not sure how long they had been fending for themselves, but they all had terrible flea dermatitis, extremely thinning hair, infected mouths, and other health issues. We have been taking care of all of their medical needs as fast as possible to make sure they are comfortable.
Blanche is a low-key dog who is content to sit beside her foster dad for hours on end. She does prefer men.
She has luxating patella (moving knee cap) in her left hind leg and needs medication for pain management. The vet also advised no climbing up or down the stairs and no long walks. So she needs to mainly use pads to do her business and be carried up and down the stairs.
She is wary of strangers and gets very nervous when they get close. She seems to be scared of other dogs who want to be friends, so she needs to be the only dog/only pet in her forever home.
Blanche lost all her teeth after her dental so she needs to be on canned or softened dry dog food. Her adoption fee is $200.

animal.description:
NAME: Maggie
Age: 1.5 yrs old
Breed: Potcake from Turks and Caicos (shepherd/collie mix)
Sex: female
Weight: 55 lbs
Location: Coldwater, ON
Spayed/Neutered: I have a medical issue that has made it not possible to be completely spayed. Medical records will be provided. 
Kids/Cats/Dogs: Not suited for young children. I've briefly met cats, I wanted to chase them. Due to high hormone levels, I cannot be with another female dog. A neutered male dog companion is best, or I would be happy as the only dog too. 
Car rides: I'm great in the car.
Crate/house trained: I am good in the house. I am crate trained but dont need to be.
Leash walks: I am good on leash and once I know you well enough, I can be off leash too. 
Vacc/worming/flea: UTD on vaccinations? Flea/tick, worming? Vet checked? Microchipped? 

Hi, my name is Maggie! I was surrendered to FEF to find a better suited home for me. After 2 surgeries the vets say I am an odd mystery. A mix of birth deformed reproductive parts, mixed with possibly trauma that has caused internal scarring and lesions has left me a mess inside. Therefore it's possible I may have ovarian remnants and possible I could still come into heat. Throughout my cycles I have spikes in hormone levels, and I fight with other females. I'm looking the perfect home that can accommodate me and my cycles. 
I'm such a lovebug. I'm shy with new people. I'm uneasy around children. I'd prefer a home without children. I'm sensitive, I like quiet homes with a low traffic lifestyle. I prefer the country rather than a busy city. The city noises make me very nervous. I really just want to be someone's best friend. To cuddle on the couch, and go for walks. That is what I dream of. If you can provide this type of home, and be able to manage my cycles, fill out an application here:
https://form.jotform.co/83008434566862
Email my foster mom for more information fureverfriendsadoption@gmail.com 
Love Maggie?

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi, I'm Mack / Petey. I'm a lovable 3.5yr old, 68lb big puppy! I love going on walks, especially runs with my humans! I have a lot of energy but calm down after a good run outside. I'm fully potty trained and will let you know when I need to go outside. I love making new dog friends at the park and seeing dogs on walks. However in my previous home over the last year and a half I had a lot of anxiety and stress with the other dogs in the home. Due to this I'm not sure how I would react to other resident dogs and may be best as a single dog home. I also love my foster cat siblings but they love me most when I respect their space. I forget how big I am compared to them so I try playing with them but they don't like it very much, but I listen to my foster mom when she says to knock it off. I know how to sit, shake, lay down and even stay! I am working on not pulling mom when we go for a walk but I listen pretty well and won't pull her across the ice. I love snuggles and will probably take up the entire bed, but I sleep all night and wait for you to wake up in the morning. I have never been left in a kennel but do very well when my humans aren't home. I love being around my foster humans and I'm learning to trust men more. I love my foster dad and foster brother but I love foster mom most!

Mack's

adoption fee includes: Full veterinary exam, dewormed, Distemper vaccines appropriate to age, Bordetella vaccine, rabies vaccine, alter, 4dx, prepaid microchip frontline and heart guard while in rescue. Adoption fee: $375.00

animal.description:
Meet this sweetheart Nala! She came into the shelter late December 2020 when her owner could no longer keep her. Nala was surrendered to us due to not getting along with the other dogs in the house. She was a walking Skelton but she was give 5 small meals a day for weeks and she looks fantastic. She gobbles her good up so quickly so she will need a “slow feeder bowl” to eat out of to ensure she doesn’t eat too fast causing bloat. She has some areas on her skin that required some medicated baths and she’s on the mend and looking and feeling much better. At first she was very nervous with new people and some times would do a low growl but she is blossoming into such an amazing pup now that’s she’s in better shape &  health.  She will need to be the only animal in her forever home. She loves OMG Surprise Toys and chew-proof toys! Nala loves to play fetch and is an absolute cuddle bug!! If you are interested in Nala and think you can provide her perfect furever home, please contact us at 252-247-7744 or stop by for a visit. 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
Bruce is a sweet & sassy Chiweenie who is 10 years old and weighs 9 lbs.  He was surrendered to animal control with 7 canine companions when their elderly owner was hospitalized and could no longer care for them.  Bruce is a loving, affectionate, adorable little snuggler who likes to crawl into your lap and be with his person.  He is a low energy boy with awesome leash manners who knows basic commands and likes to take walks around his neighborhood.  He has humongous ears that never go down & tower over his teeny, tiny head! The conditions in Bruce's previous home were very bad and Bruce came to BarkVille with flea dermatitis which caused some hair loss.  However, BarkVille treated that condition and his hair is returning a little more each day.  Bruce is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  

For more information about Bruce, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet boy, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Peppermint Patty is a 2 year old spayed female lab mix who weighs about 49 lbs. She was rescued from an overcrowded high kill shelter after being picked up as a stray. There is no one sweeter than Peppermint Patty! She is a charmer and wins over everyone she meets. If you have love to give she will be there to receive it. This love bug craves attention and will accept every pet she is offered. Peppermint Patty seems to be pretty well-mannered and eager to please. She's been good with the other dogs she has met and didn't pay attention to the kitties she saw outside. She will follow you around like a little puppy, interested in everything you do. We're not sure what her previous life was like, but we've promised her a bright future! She may have limited vision out of one eye as it is either deformed or suffered an old injury, but it doesn't slow her down. We just adore this sweetheart and cannot wait to find her the perfect forever home... could it be yours??

PS: We've sent Ms. Patty for a pedicure since this photo was taken. 

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq
Follow us on Facebook for foster updates and a full list of our adoptable pets: https://www.facebook.com/all4pawsrescue/

animal.description:
Meet this cutie named Abby! She came into the shelter mid January 2021 when her owner could no longer keep her. She is 10 years 5 months old, current on shots, already spayed, and house broken. We were told she could be quirky when rubbing on her if you got around her back end. She has been in a foster home with another pup and has been perfect...no issues. She has played with a few dogs at the shelter and has been great thus far. She is a great sized pup and other than having a little “hazy” look in her eyes you would have no idea she is 10 years plus. She’s  happy and full of love to share. Would do best in a home without young children since previous owners said she could be quirky. We like to make sure past info is passed down to those interested but in previous situations with other animals we have learned it may have been something in the home or environment that triggered behaviors that we never see at the shelter.  If you’re interested in Abby please reach out to the shelter and a meet and greet with this cutie can be arranged. 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

Felicia is a beautiful 8 month old Aussie girl with pricked up ears and a smiley face. She loves to run around the yard with her foster siblings and that really IS her happy place. She is an extremely timid little girl around humans and will take lots of patience and love to gain her trust as well as a confident dog brother/sister will be best for her future home. She is crate trained and is making great progress with house training but will have accidents.

Felicia would not do well in an apartment situation and needs a physically fenced yard to run around and burn some energy. She is low-medium energy and will need help with leash training and socialization. She will be best suited with an experienced Aussie owner who will be able to help Felicia to become a confident/happy pup. Although she is okay with the kids in her foster home, we do not recommend a home with kids under the age of 8 years old. 

Felicia is approximately 8 months, 25 pounds, UTD on vaccines and spayed. She is being fostered in Orlando, Florida and a meet and greet will be required.

If you think Felicia is the right fit for you, please fill out our application:

https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Name: Jackson
Age, Weight Gender: 8- 10 years; 60lbs; Male
Dog friendly/required?: Yes/No
Cat Friendly: Unknown
Fenced yard required?: No
Housetrained: Yes
Crate trained: yes
Children: yes
Temperament: Low energy; mellow

Jackson is between 8-10 years of age and is 60 lbs. As you can see in the pictures he is a senior who obviously knows how to have a good time:). He is a black lab/hound mix. His face and coloring looks lab, but his conformation has some hound aspects to it. He is typically very quiet (even when other dogs are going nuts due to the UPS man) but on occasion he will bay/howl like a hound.

He was picked up as a stray several times. His owner had received several warnings about Jackson’s poor condition. If the owner had picked him up this last time, he would have been ticketed… We pulled him after his “stray hold” time was up.

He is slightly hard of hearing and has cataracts. He has been accidentally surprised a few times so while he is in a foster home with children ranging from 7 years to college age, he may be best in a quieter household.

Jackson is a hard core couch potato. He also has a bladder of steel. This combination would be ideal for someone who works long shifts (like a nurse). He would also be well suited for apartment life. He may need help up and down stairs later in life so a first floor apartment or access to an elevator may *eventually* be necessary.

He does not want to play with other dogs, but does like roaming through underbrush (following his nose). He does well with other medium to low energy dogs. He gives warning growls when other dogs jump on him wanting to play. He is fine if they want to nap near him, eat near him, or even share a crate. If another dog starts zooming around the yard, he promptly exits the area.

Jackson gets fed 2.5 cups of softened senior dog food in the morning and 2.5 cups in the evening. He will beg for pets and generally nag you until you feed him if you forget. He is housebroken. Never had an accident in the house. He whines to go outside to potty. Jackson knows “sit”. “Get down” off the sofa or bed. He’s not a fan of dog bones (they’re hard), but does like cheese, and freeze dried chicken.

Jackson was neutered and had his front teeth removed due to their poor condition. He eats his food carefully. The foster typically softens the kibble with water about 30 min before being fed(just in case). He started his heartworm treatment on January 4 and should be ready for travel mid-March.

This boy has won over the hearts of everyone he has met in both Jackson Mississippi and HOH rescues. He is a mellow guy that would make a great companion.

animal.description:
Many people shy away from a mature dog, but there is so much joy that can be had from taking an older dog into your family.  While we shy away from calling our IZZY a "senior dog", this female Black Lab would qualify for the canine AARP with an estimated DOB of 12/2012.  Izzy came to FOPAS from a not-good situation, in fact she had spent her entire life outside in the heat and cold.  Now that she's inside, with a soft bed in the warmth, she is ready to enjoy these comforts for the rest of her life.  This is a very happy dog!  Izzy is so so affectionate, if she could sit in someone's lap all the time she would.  However, at 57 pounds, she usually only gets her head in the lap, which is plenty for her.  Izzy doesn't like to be left outside by herself (as you can imagine) but if someone is with her, or taking her for a walk, she is a wonderful companion.  Izzy used to live with many other dogs, so she can probably live with other dogs but at FOPAS she has spent her time with her "sister" Lenore with whom she came from her former life.  A meet and greet with a potential sibling would be needed.  If you are looking for love and contentment and happiness your dog is IZZY!!

If you are interested in Izzy, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

Welcome Raven to the pack. Raven is a 4 month old Husky/Pitt mix.
Raven is a friendly, people focused puppy who is a fast learner with a lot of puppy energy.
Her short hair means she doesnt shed much and shes very cuddly and loves nothing better than sleeping on your lap. But because of her husky background, she loves being active and has a lot of energy that needs to be focused.
Shes great with other dogs and often sleeps on her foster brothers back. She loves playing rough with the other dogs and can hold her own even with a big dog. Shes just learning to walk on a leash because her immunizations were just finalized, but shes fully potty trained as long as she has access to the outdoors and is used to going out with the other dogs at regular intervals.
She loves to chew and is very good about chewing on dog toys as long as she has them. Shes going to make someone a wonderful pet although she does tend to like one person in particular. Raven weighs approximately 25lbs and would do best in a home with kids over the age of five.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please review our adoption process and then fill out an online adoption form at https://www.calpaws.org/adopting. Sampson does need a family that is willing to put in time to get him exercise everyday, and he needs a secure fenced backyard. He will not stay on farm property without a fence as he wants to wander and play with all the neighbor dogs. He does need a home WITHOUT cats as he will chase them.

Fill out an application at the link below. Find the dog/cat you are interested in and click the adopt button. That will take you to an application. Once approved you will be called for an appointment to meet your possible new family member, or at that time you can meet the other animals as well. https://petstablished.com/public/search/shelter/301551

Adoption fee is $150 which includes, spay/neuter, vaccines, etc, and a free 1 year membership to our 5 acre ARF Park. For other dog questions please email ARFdogs74006@gmail.com

We do adopt out of state, but the adopter must travel to ARF to meet the dog they are looking to adopt. They must have an approved application before traveling to meet the dog. We do allow small dogs that are eligible to fly in the cabin of a plane. We DO NOT allow dogs to travel in the cargo area of the plane under any circumstances. Any dog that is adopted can of course go by personal vehicle. We do not allow dogs to be transported "pony express style" where they are passed from driver to driver.

animal.description:
On the outskirts of Houston lies a small outdoor shelter. They do their best out there, but the kennels are fully exposed to the elements except for a few wimpy tarps they put up in a desperate attempt to protect dogs from the winds. They had no idea what they were going to do to keep these dogs safe from the freezing weather, their only solution was to take the dogs to their personal homes. But with only a couple of staff members, there was not enough space in their homes for Portugal. He was going to be left out to freeze if they didn't reach out for help.

In a last ditch effort to get him safe from the freezing weather, an employee out there reached out to us for help. So hours before temperatures plummeted in Houston, Portugal was brought to us, with no plan except to keep her safe from the weather. Luckily we were able to place him into a foster home, where he has been doing fantasticly! I would try to put it into my own words, but I think it's best to let the foster tell you himself:

"Portugal is one of the sweetest dogs weve ever had the blessing of fostering. She is very attentive and listens to your commands when you tell her to sit, lie down, or stop whatever she is doing. If you want her to sit down, raise your fist up like youre holding a treat. She likes to snuggle more than play fetch and she LOVES it when you scratch her under her chin or rub her belly. She has a beautiful coat and the biggest pair of brown puppy dog eyes that will melt your heart." This is all the information we have currently.


	Approved Applicants may make the adoption fee payment by clicking donate above. Partial adoption fees will not hold a dog.
	Dogs adopted with our rescue come with FREE training from #GoodPup to help you build strong bonds from the start!
	If upon meeting the dog of your choosing at an adoption event you find that you aren't a good match, your deposit will be refunded minus a 10% administration fee.
	Adoption fees include vaccines up until time of adoption, microchip, spay/neuter and 1st 30 days of free Pet insurance. We are not affiliated with Pet First pet insurance. (you have to sign up for the insurance or it will not go into effect). 
	Adopters can go to our vet for medical issues that may arise in 1st 3 days of adoption. 
	The dogs in our care are fostered in Colorado, Texas, and New Mexico. While all dogs are picked up during our scheduled times, sometimes transport dates change due to unforeseen circumstances.

animal.description:
Sweet Dopey is a staff favorite. Dopey is in early stage liver disease but that is easily managed with a good diet and care.The following are staff notes on his behavior in the Texas shelter he was rescued from: Approached kennel and dog was sitting with a neutral body. I offered treats through the gate and dog extended neck out slowly. After sniffing treat, he took treat from my hand with a very soft mouth. After he ate treat he stood up and had a soft swaying body and tail. I got low and opened gate offering more treats and dogs body became wiggly as he approached me and began eating treats out of my hands. 

HW+ simply means the dog has tested positive for heart worms in our screening process. We utilize what is called the fast-kill method which means we place the dog on antibiotics for 30 days and then administer 3 injections in increments afterward. The cost to treat heart worms is rather steep. However, thanks to our generous donors, we are able to cover that cost for our adopters so long as they go to our veterinarian, Red Rocks Animal Center in Lakewood.

animal.description:
I am a one year old pup that goes by Levi. I have been through a lot of not so great stuff so now I am hoping to settle down with my very own forever family. I like humans and other dogs but Im not sure about cats as Ive never had one before. Im willing to give them a try though as I hear they can be great fun! 

Im a bit of a ladies man but I will give the guys an equal opportunity as long as they give me a little while to accept them into my circle. I prefer humans that are at least ten years old so they wont interfere with my getting all the attention.

I am potty trained but have something called urethral Sphincter Hypotonus. What's that? My foster mom says thats why is just sometimes leak and dribble when I walk. Doc game me some meds and I am now neutered so we hope that solves things. However, it's too early to tell if this is temporary of permanent but I have adapted quite well to a belly band. I will let you know when I need to go out. I dont like the cold so I just want to do my business and come right back inside. Please dont dawdle! When the weather is warmer I will probably be willing to stay outside and play with you if you like.

I am smart, eager to learn and I am already working on sit, stay, down and come. I am a little insecure and will require some reassurance that I am safe and loved. I like to sit very close to (or directly on) my humans and I love to be held and given gentle pets. Loud sounds and fast movements can make me feel a bit scared but I am learning to be more confident. I spent a lot of time in a crate that was too small for me so I do not yet see the crate as my safe haven.

If you will help me overcome my little insecurities and fears I promise I will love you with my whole heart! I also promise you will never get to sit alone again!

animal.description:
Best cuddler for a snowy day!

Hey guys! I know it's cold inside and I am here to make it cozy. I am Anna, an 8 months old, 17 lbs, female Yorkshire Terrier mix. I am a young lady from the Imperial County Shelter, and we were un'frozen' and rescued by TAP to find our forever homes. I have been hanging out at my foster home and pick up manners befitting a princess. I am house trained and leash trained, and just polishing up my bathroom habits. A few corrections and positive reinforcements will be great for me! I have spay plans all set for me. Just a point to remember is that my right paw is a hint more delicate than the left one and petting there should be gentle. But nothing too shabby and I am in great health, otherwise!

I have not met a whole lot of dogs or cats to know how we'd be together, but gosh, I adore kids! Little humans and I are thick together and they make me olaf so much! I cuddle hard with my 2 year old baby brother. I do have a tendency to be shy at first, but then I 'let it go' real soon! I enjoy being wrapped in a blanket burrito and nuzzle in laps. I get so happy when my family comes back and I cant help but dance with all the love.

I am a gentle lady and life with me like a cozy cocoa on a white Christmas day! I would love a mellow family with sweet kids who adore me and treat me like the royal princess that I am. If you think we can be besties together, like Anna and Elsa, give me a woof! My adoption fee is $500 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here: https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Meet 2yr old, 50lb Rocky the black pittie girl. She is a shy girl who is just waiting to burst at the seams with personality. We rescued her from a high kill shelter where she was doomed being timid. She is very friendly once she trust you. She loves toys and is truly silly. She is dog friendly and would do great following anothers lead. She is smart and food motivated. So far doing well on both house and crate training. She is a true love! She does have some very weird scarred marking on her head and feet. She is afraid of loud noises so only recommend older kids and patient experienced owner. 

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $300, which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

animal.description:
In the short time that LENORE has been with FOPAS she has made such great strides!  When she first come to us from a not-very-good situation where she was outside all the time she was so frightened of everything that she just crawled along the floor to go outside.  Now, Lenore stands for the leash to be attached and walks right out.  She is still afraid of large trucks but who isn't?  Once in the yard Lenore is a whirlwind.  She loves to play and run and play some more.  Lenore is a female English Coonhound with an estimated DOB of 7/2017.   Like most Coonhounds she is a tolerant and very gentle dog who loves to curl up in the house and relax.  Coonhounds are also very intelligent dogs with good problem solving skills.  Lenore will follow a scent so a yard with a good fence or leash walks are necessary.  This is a very sweet dog who will pay back the love given to her ten fold. Even though she has improved a lot, she will require a confident dog that shows her the ropes and help her with her confidence as well.

If you are interested in Lenore, please fill out an application here:
https://www.parkvilleshelter.com/adoption-application

animal.description:
“Come on! Let’s go for a walk!” ...and that’s  when it happens...tail-wagging joy as you affix the leash to the collar and and head out the door. Well, not so for our handsome youngster, Hamlet. He sees a leash and retreats in fear, his body shaking uncontrollably. Eventually, he’ll attack the leash. Never the human. Just the leash. Why he is so afraid of leashes we don’t know. We do know that his owner died, and he landed in the shelter where he stayed for over a month. We also know he is a sweet, gentle soul who wants desperately to love and be loved. He truly enjoys being petted from the tip of his nose to the tip of his tail, a tail that begins wagging ever so slightly as we enter his kennel. Hamlet needs time, patience, and love for his confidence to grow and his fear to subside. He would do best in a home that is calm and predictable. A house with a yard is preferable since he’ll be learning that a leash opens doors to joyful, not frightening, experiences. Hamlet is neutered, microchipped, and current on his vaccines. So, who out there is ready to show Hamlet the happy world that awaits him?

To see our other dogs, please visit www.perfectpetrescue.com.

animal.description: Nutter Butter #7620 is a 9-year-old female Chihuahua mix. She is friendly, gentle and calm. She has a low energy level, and her favorite things are soft pillows. Nutter Butter is good with other dogs and kids. She is house trained and knows the commands: sit, stay, down and off. She also walks well on the leash. While Nutter Butter is a little overweight, she doesn’t really care about treats. Ultimately, she is super sweet and likes receiving attention. She especially likes to be held. Due to her docile nature, she would do well in an apartment home. She does have a heart murmur that does not require medication at this time.  She weighs 14 pounds and should lose a little weight. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Maggie is a 1 and a half year old spayed female Hound/Black and Tan Coonhound mix (according to the vets). She is extremely smart, curious, athletic, super cute, quick to learn, mid to low energy, loves to nap in the sun, and is super cuddly at night. She is house trained, crate trained, sleeps like a log through the night, and knows her basic commands.

Maggie can be reactive to her environment, out of fear. She obviously has been through a lot, and is very easily frightened. In a calm house with a calm person, she does wonderful! Things like bikes, skateboards, some noises like clicking, and cars make her react fearfully, so she will need someone who has the resources, patience, and time to commit fully and consistently with a trainer to desensitize and re-condition her so she has the skills to be successful. She is a quick and eager learner, so we are confident she will be comfortable in her environment over time. She can be dog selective (she likes some and doesn't like others). Slow introductions with dogs and new people is good. She gets a bit nervous in a car and around some noises (like ticking, so training with a clicker is not a good idea) but is not fearful of most household noises like washing machines and dishwashers. We wish we knew what happened in her past to cause these fears! She often seeks reassurance and comfort, and responds quite well to positive reinforcement. 

She does not have any destructive behaviors at all (no digging, chewing, nibbling, etc.) which is great! Ideally, her adoptive family is energetic and retired or works from home full time and lives in a rural environment or at least has a large back yard for her to run and explore for exercise (she loves to watch and chase squirrels) while she learns to play with toys and to take walks. A 6’ privacy fence is a must. 

Maggie comes with her own memory foam bed, crate, harnesses, training gear, sweaters, and enrichment toys if her new family wants them. Maggie is super sweet and loyal to those who care for and love her.

Maggie will be up to date on her vetting/vaccinations to be in line with our commitment to only adopting out healthy dogs. She will also be spayed to support our work for zero population growth in dogs.

Maggie is ready for adoption now! Applications are currently being accepted for this very sweet loving and loyal best friend. An application can be found at http://farfels.com/farfels-rescue/adoption-form/. If interested in our wonderful puppy, please fill out completely and submit.

**PLEASE NOTE** If you're truly interested in adopting from us, please be sure to fill out our Farfel's Rescue adoption application found at the link above or at farfels.com. Adoption site applications such as Petfinder, Rescueme and Adoptapet don't provide enough information and therefore aren't useful. Our Farfel's application is the only initial tool that we have to determine a great match for this very deserving dog. We're sorry, but in most cases, we're unable to get back to those that don't submit our Farfel's Rescue adoption application. Thanks very much for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
Cody is a four month old lab possible shep mix about 20 pounds at this time. We really don't know the breed. He came to the shelter as a stray, waited on stray hold and no one came to get him so he's available for a new and forever home. He's young and been on the streets. He's not house trained and doesn't have any basic commands. He will need all that when he gets into his new home. He's good with other dogs and humans at the shelter but has not been around very young children. He's not been cat tested. He has average energy for his age and possible breed and seems to shed moderately. He's happy and playful without being "too much" and seems to love attention. 

 He is currently in Fort Worth, TX but can make the trek to Olympia, WA scheduled to arrive on Saturday Feb 6th	 with a pre-adoption which is the only way to secure that he will for sure go home with you! Pre-Adoption means getting your app in, approved and paying the adoption fee to secure the ride.  His adoption fee is $450 which covers his neuter, vaccinations, HW testing, chipping, health certificate and transport fees. All our dogs come with a 30 day, money back, trial period to make sure they are the right fit in your environment. Tall Tails Rescue has a commitment to these dogs for their lifetime and we hope you do too! If you are interested in pre-adoption you can click the link here or copy/paste and fill out the app to get started: https://form.jotform.com/PNWdogs/ttrt-pnw-ap

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Casper (TX) is a male Pit Bull Terrier mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Casper is 2 years old at the time of intake in January 2021. Casper is good with people and other dogs. It's a conflict of emotions when we stare in the face of overwhelming love and fury in the same dog. Love when we look at Casper's sweet face, and fury when we look at the brutal wounds Casper suffered at the hands of the monster who tied him to a car and dragged him almost to his death and then left him on the side of the road to finish dying. But Casper cheated death that day, and he will now go on to a live a life that will far exceed the miserable existence of the savage that did this to Casper. Casper's eyes show a life of sadness and defeat, but we are determined to turn his life around and replace that sadness with a life of love and happiness. If you would like to lead Casper on his journey to a happy life, please appy online to adopt Casper (TX) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description: Meet amazing Eloise! She is an active senior at 9 1/2 years young. Adorable and a lovely mix of Chihuahua and terrier to make for a cute and compact 40lb. medium-sized doll. Eloise has such a bright spirit and is ready to go anytime. She will get you out for walks, make you laugh, give you love, and cuddle with you! She prefers a calmer household so no kiddo's or other pets please. She is Ok with apt living as long as she gets ample time outdoors with walks. If you have a yard, even better! She will do best with an experienced owner rather than a first-time pup parent. Eloise really wants you to herself and is not into other dogs. She can get overly excited if they get to close but responds to redirection. Eloise walks well on the leash, is house trained, knows a few tricks and has a bright personality that keeps you smiling and on your toes. This cutie pie loves human companionship, will be your best friend, and will take ear scratches and belly rubs as often as you will give them. She will take a little time to settle into your home, and we will give you tips on how to ease her in. Eloise is in great health and shows no signs of slowing down. She is current on all shots, spayed, and micro-chipped. Upon adoption we will provide a transition session! Any questions, email raincityrescue@gmail.com or to complete an application go to, raincityrescue.com/adopt.  This amazing girl can’t wait for her awesome new life with you!

animal.description:
Ellie Mae / Female / 3 Years / 60 lbs / Catahoula Leopard Dog / Brampton

Meet Ellie Mae! Ellie comes to us all the way from from Hohenwald, Tennesee! Almost two years ago, Ellie had a litter of puppies who quickly came to Canada and all found loving forever homes. Recently Ellie had her chance and made the long trip to Canada in search of a family to call her own. Ellie has spent the last few weeks decompressing in foster care and learning the joys of being a pet. She is looking for a patient family with some dog experience who can begin to expose her true potential.

Ellie Mae takes time to trust people, and is still opening up to her foster parents. Now she will come to the door to greet them and even wag her tail when her foster parents come home. When new people enter the home she may come in view of the door but generally won’t come closer than 10 feet. She will choose not to approach and her space should be respected at all times. Continued socialization and positive experiences with new people will be an ongoing part of her training. She has not been tested with children but we predict their unpredictable movements and energy may be overwhelming for Ellie.

Ellie has not been left alone much in foster care but is not a fan of her crate. She has likely had little exposure to them and does not like being confined. She has taken particular liking to her foster Dad and will follow him wherever he goes in the home. She will need adopters willing to introduce some boundaries and encourage structured alone time. She would do best with a puppy proofed space when left alone instead of a crate.

Ellie is new to life in the home and is just learning that she needs to use the washroom outside. She still has accidents in the home and will generally choose the same spot. She is very sensitive, so she is only responsive to force-free/positive reinforcement based training. It is difficult to get close enough to put her harness/leash on and it usually takes two people to do so. Once she is outside though, its difficult to get her back inside! Ellie will need a calm and patient family who has a good understanding of the work ahead.

Ellie does not know any commands yet but once she is fully comfortable in her new home, she will benefit from obedience and trick training. She is reluctant to walk on leash and is very overwhelmed by everything outside. She is fearful of cars, people, dogs and will usually choose to walk behind her people. She will rarely use the washroom on walks and needs time to adjust to a new environment.

Ellie Mae is only looking for homes outside of the city, and preferably in farm/quiet country. She will need a fully secured place to play outside and use the washroom. She is still very anxious about the world around her and will need experienced adopters who are committed to building her confidence. Ellie has only shown fear towards other dogs so would likely prefer to be the only dog in the home. This may change with slow/proper introductions to other calm dogs. She has a very high prey drive so is only looking for homes without cats.

If you’re interested in adopting Ellie Mae please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Ellie Mae’s adoption fee is $800. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

If you think Spencer may be the one for you, please go to our website at www.wagstorichesanimalrescue.org and fill out an application to adopt. Spencer is neutered, microchipped, fecal tested clean of internal parasites and up to date on all his vaccinations.

animal.description: Tiger Lily #7638 is a 2-year-old female Pit Bull mix. She is a friendly but shy young lady. She is a very mellow girl and has low energy. She is very calm when meeting other dogs, and doesn’t seem to pay attention to them. We recommend a slow introduction to any potential housemates. Tiger Lily should be in a home without cats. She is crate trained and walks well on the leash. She doesn’t seem to care about treats. We encourage her new family to continue socializing her with people and other dogs. Tiger Lily is an LCAR mom and came to us with puppies in tow. Now that they have been weaned, it’s her turn for some R&R and a home of her own. She also came to us with heartworms. We are seeking an adopter that will continue her treatment, provided by LCAR, at no additional cost. This adoption will be considered a foster to adopt. She weighs 55 pounds and should gain a few pounds. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. animal.description:
Bolo / Male / 1 Year / 60 lbs / Boxer Mix / Scarborough

Meet Bolo! Bolo was rescued off the streets of Mexico City when he was just a puppy. He was adopted out but then returned when the family felt ill-equipped to handle his energy level and the specific needs of a deaf dog. Lucky for Bolo he ended up in the loving hands of our partner shelter. Once he was cleared to travel, he made the long trip to Canada in search of his forever home!

Bolo is a very happy dog and when he meets new people he has the most wiggly bum you’ll ever see. He is described as loving, goofy, playful, social, smart and energetic. His favorite spot in the whole world is to be cuddled up next to his people. He loves to chew bones and stuffed kongs. He also loves stuffy toys but true to the boxer in him, has a tendency to be a bit rough with them. He is starting to learn fetch and has gotten pretty good at returning the ball. He will make the ultimate side-kick to a special family who doesn’t see his deafness as a disability, as it doesn’t slow him down at all!

Bolo loves to meet all people, and will be at the first at the door welcoming strangers (or his family) into the home. He is still learning how to play respectfully with humans, and can be mouthy at times. He has already made massive improvements in foster care but is not looking for homes with small children. Although he has never shown signs of aggression, with his play and size would prefer homes with dog savvy children that are ages 10+.

Bolo is on the higher side of medium energy and currently getting a long walk in the morning plus lots of time to play in the backyard. He is smart and is learning a “potty sign” to open the lines of communication. He potty breaks are scheduled but if he is sniffing around a spot more than usual, he will be let outside using the “potty sign” and lots of praise signing “yes” once he goes in the right place. An adjustment period should be expected when he enters a new environment.

Bolo is a great walker on leash and has not expressed any fears. He is being walked on a gentle leader and when he loses focus, it is easy to regain his attention with gentle correction on his harness. The gentle leader is not for pulling but for allowing another form of communication while outside. He is easily walked with a loose leash in heal position.

Bolo is a very agile dog and has jumped right on the dining room table before. He will need a 6-8 foot fence in his backyard, anything lower he can likely pounce over. Regardless he can be driven when he wants something, so will alway require supervison while in his backyard. Due to his deafness, he will never be suitable for off leash/unsecured time outdoors.

He is currently learning hand signals for all basic commands. He is learning sit, stat, potty, yes, no, eating, now, leave it, happy and recall within closed spaces. Bolo is smart and always eager to learn. His foster Mom says his current roster of commands is just for the beginning for him! He is still very much a puppy and will need support with basic house manners. He will try to put anything and everything in his mouth, and may chew things if he is bored and unsupervised. Adopters should be comfortable with consistent redirection as needed.

For many deaf dogs, they become anxious when separated from their people. It will take time to work through it with Bolo as he can be vocal when left alone. He has never been destructive but has only been left alone for short periods. As a precaution the bars of his crate are sprayed with bitter apple to limit his drive to escape.

Bolo’s ideal home would be a detached house, with a fully fenced backyard. He would be fine in city or suburban life, as long as his exercise needs are met. Bolo loves the company of other dogs but can’t hear “back off cues” so will need initial stages of relationships to be managed by his humans. He would also be fine as the only dog in the home, where he can be the centre of attention all day! Bolo has not been tested with cats.

Bolo is a Boxer mix with his full tail. He’s a powerful wagger and suffers from “Happy Tail”. He wears a fashionable tail wrap so he can wag to his heart’s content without worries of re-injury. Adopters will need to keep an eye on his tail and ensure he does not re-injure it. A Tractive GPS will be a requirement of Bolo's adoption, because he is deaf.

If you’re interested in adopting Bolo please apply at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/adoption-info#adoption-form

Bolo’s adoption fee is $700. To learn more about our adoption fees and the adoption process, please visit our FAQs at https://www.fetchandreleash.ca/about-us#about-faqs.

His favorite things are chew toys, balls, and squeaky toys. Bubba is comfortable in his crate where he sleeps through the night and retires for daytime naps. About Foster to Adopt Program:
Fosters provide a safe landing spot for dogs transitioning from the shelter environment and help prepare the dogs for adoption. You provide the love and structure, and we take care of everything else! We cover all vet care, and drive the adoption process. Average length of foster is 2-3 weeks. Fosters do get first consideration for adoption, if desired.
